alt: The image shows two young boys sitting together on a porch, with one boy smiling at the camera. Both are wearing casual clothing, with one in a denim jacket and the other in a blue hoodie. The background features a house with horizontal siding and a metal railing. The text overlay reads, "Refugees did not choose to become refugees." In the bottom left corner, the logo and text "airbnb.org" are displayed.
caption:
Every year on World Refugee Day we honor all those forced to flee their homes. Zyad, Souzan, and their four children who fled the civil war in Syria are among more than 110 million refugees worldwide.

“When you realize you’re not going back, you feel like you’ve lost everything you’ve built in your life,” Zyad said. His family moved to the US this year through a sponsorship program from Welcome Corps and the Integrated Refugee and Immigrant Services. For their first month in the country, they stayed in a home for free through airbnb.org.

Now the kids are in school, the family has moved into permanent housing, and they’re rebuilding their lives with the help of their new community. Meet Zyad and Souzan, and learn how airbnb.org has provided free, temporary housing for more than 210,000 refugees to date at the link in our bio.

#WorldRefugeeDay

caption:
“We need to make time to make people feel happy. It’s the same as hosting on Airbnb when you welcome someone into your house,” says Emmanuel, who has been a Host in Paris for more than 10 years. 

He’s also a volunteer with a nonprofit that serves people who are in distress or alone by organizing weekly gatherings and community meals. Emmanuel nominated the nonprofit for an Airbnb Community Fund donation. 

The Community Fund will distribute $100 million USD by the end of 2030 to strengthen communities around the world.

caption:
Donations to Airbnb.org help people like Elif find a place to call home during times of crisis. 

After working with humanitarian organizations for eight years, Elif suddenly found herself on the receiving end of emergency aid. She lost her home and everything inside during the 2023 earthquakes in Türkiye and Syria. She was staying 3 hours away, though through Airbnb.org she found a place in Hatay. This saved Elif the long commute, giving her more time and space to focus on her job.

“When I stayed in an Airbnb, I could go home and relax. When I woke up the next day, I was energized and ready to do my job. I could motivate my team.”

alt: A man stands leaned against a wall while looking towards a Ukrainian flag that waves in the background. The man has gray hair, and a blue shirt. He is slightly smiling.
caption:
Rafał could sense the impact in the weeks after Russia invaded Ukraine on his hometown of Wrocław, Poland. Boxes of donated supplies piled up outside a Ukrainian cultural center in his neighborhood. He heard Ukrainian spoken on the streets.

According to the U.N. Human Rights Council, more than 6 million people fled Ukraine in the six months following the February 2022 invasion. Millions of families arrived in cities all over Europe with just a few suitcases and no idea when they might return home.

In response to the crisis, Airbnb.org put out a call to its nonprofit partners and global community of Hosts: Can you help us offer temporary housing to up to 100,000 people fleeing Ukraine?

Offers of support and donations flooded in. Since then, Airbnb.org has met its commitment by connecting 100,000 people affected by the war with temporary housing.

Some of the 40,000 people who signed up to host refugees, like Rafał, are longtime Airbnb Hosts who offer stays for free or at a discount through Airbnb.org. Others learned about Airbnb.org by searching online for ways to help.

Rafał says the invasion of Ukraine threw everyone he knew in Poland into a state of shock, yet he was amazed by how quickly his friends and neighbors responded to the influx of people fleeing the war.

Within days of the invasion, three families from Ukraine booked monthlong stays, back to back, at the house he lists on Airbnb. Concerned about charging people fleeing a war, Rafał contacted Airbnb customer service, learned that Airbnb.org could subsidize his efforts, and signed up. Rafał continues to list his house through Airbnb.org to welcome guests displaced by crises.

alt: Two women sit together at a table talking. They each have a mug in front of them, and in the background there is a large green plant with sprawling leaves.
caption:
“A lot of times, with the efforts that we put into things, we don’t necessarily see the results. But with this, I could make a difference in at least one person’s life.”

In the weeks after Russia invaded Ukraine, Mary—an American living in Berlin—knew she wanted to do something to help. When she saw Airbnb.org’s call to action online, she listed her apartment free of charge.

Soon after, Dima arrived to stay for two weeks. A man in his 20s, Dima was living in Kyiv when Russians began bombing the city. A grassroots organization named Safebow helped Dima and his hairless cat, Peach, travel through Poland to Berlin. There, Airbnb.org’s partner the Organization for Refuge, Asylum, and Migration (ORAM) helped him find housing and register for social services.

After a trip filled with obstacles, arriving at Mary’s apartment was a relief for Dima and they immediately clicked. They spent hours at her kitchen table, sharing meals and drinking beers, and stayed in touch after he moved into another apartment.

“It was a gigantic boost to my start here,” Dima says.

Mary and Dima’s story is just one of thousands. Airbnb.org’s global community has shown us the difference one person can make.

If you or someone you know has a space to share, here’s how to help:

2. If you’re not already an Airbnb.org Host, we’ll guide you through the process
3. The organizations we work with on the ground will verify guests’ eligibility

Some notes:
—Airbnb.org Hosts offer short-term stays for free
—Existing Hosts can offer a discount or offer their place for free
—Airbnb.org guests don't pay anything
—Airbnb provides Hosts with AirCover, which includes $1 million USD in liability insurance, $3 million USD in damage protection, and more
—Airbnb waives Host and guest service fees on all Airbnb.org stays

You can still support these efforts even if you don’t have a space to share. 100% of all donations to Airbnb.org fund emergency stays. #mauifires #volunteer

alt: A smiling person laying in a mess of pink blankets and sheets in a bed with a cream headboard. Orange and yellow Tulips stand in a clear glass vase on a tall wooden circular side table with long triangular legs. A large black framed photo of a tennis court with a white house compound and mountains in the background hangs above the bed. A pink border lines the right side of the frame.
caption:
William Krisel tract homes have become the iconic mid-century architecture associated with Palm Springs. Originally designed in the 1950s as contemporary housing, these homes all contain his signature clerestory windows, breezeways, and seamless outdoor/indoor floor plans.

Glass Cabin designed by William Krisel, found in our Design Category.
📸 @chantalaanderson

A robin's egg blue mid century modern lounge chair with an ottoman sits in the foreground.
childPosts/4/alt: A corner of a plywood built-in kitchen with a white double oven sitting to the left and framed by the cabinets. A person stands on a white chair looking into the top plywood shelf. The plywood shelf opens to the ceiling and clear glass is stacked nesting inside.  On the left two shallow wooden shelves sit above the other, the top shelf has a white teapot on the right side and three Matryoshka sculptures on the left. The lower shelf has clear glasses and pink mugs, plates and bowls spread evenly down it. A gold pot filler hangs over a black grated stove top with a silver tea kettle resting on the front burner. On the white marble counter to the left of the stove is salt and pepper mills, olive oil, a wooden box with cooking utensils standing up, and a hodgepodge of bags lay next to a tomato on a cutting board.
